<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="70" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,1437,1229,1975]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,350,1349,1375]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Description.</emphasis>
Hydroid colony pleustonic, polymorphic, with disc-shaped mantle overlying a chitinous float. Upper surface of mantle and float slightly concave, with scattered hollow papillae, central pore and peripheral stigmata indistinct; lower surface with one short, broad central gastrozooid, a medial ring of gonozooids, and a peripheral ring of dactylozooids, with most gonozooids and dactylozooids missing in present material. Gonozooids vermiform to club-shaped, with nematocyst knobs scattered over body and arranged in a whorl at distal end. Dactylozooids club-shaped, somewhat triangular in cross-section distally, with short capitate tentacles in three vertical rows over body and arranged in a whorl at distal end. Nematocyst reservoir disc-shaped, internal, between gastrozooid and float.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,1437,1229,1975]" box="[198,1031,1669,1695]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Gonophores free medusae, arising in clusters from base of gonozooids.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="70" lastPageNumber="71" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,1437,1229,1975]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,319,1709,1735]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Remarks.</emphasis>
The taxonomy of this hydrozoan was thoroughly reviewed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bigelow, H. B." box="[1074,1262,1709,1735]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="171 - 402" refId="ref50508" refString="Bigelow, H. B. (1911) Reports on the scientific results of the expedition to the eastern tropical Pacific, in charge of Alexander Agassiz, by the U. S. Fish Commission steamer &quot; Albatross &quot;, from October 1904, to March, 1905, Lieut. Commander L. M. Garrett, U. S. N., commanding. XXIII. The Siphonophorae. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College, 38, 171 - 402." type="journal article" year="1911">Bigelow (1911)</bibRefCitation>
. While he recognized 
<taxonomicName authority="Lesson, 1826" authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1826" box="[252,611,1749,1775]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Porpitidae" genus="Porpita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="pacifica">
<emphasis box="[252,444,1749,1774]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Porpita pacifica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lesson, R. P." box="[453,611,1749,1775]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" refId="ref59550" refString="Lesson, R. P. (1826) Voyage autour du monde, execute par l'ordre du Roi, sur la corvette de sa majeste, &quot; la Coquille, &quot; pendant les annees 1822, 1823, 1824 et 1825. Histoire naturelle, zoologie. Atlas. Zoophytes. A. Bertrand, Paris, 16 pl." type="journal volume" year="1826">Lesson, 1826</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
as the valid name for the species in the Pacific Ocean, 
<bibRefCitation author="Moser, F." box="[1274,1437,1749,1775]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="1 - 541" refId="ref61523" refString="Moser, F. (1925) Die Siphonophoren der Deutschen Sudpolar - Expedition 1901 - 1903. Deutsche Sudpolar-Expedition 1901 - 1903, 17 (Zoologie 9), 1 - 541." type="journal article" year="1925">Moser (1925)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Totton, A. K." box="[202,365,1789,1815]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="1 - 162" refId="ref65848" refString="Totton, A. K. (1954) Siphonophora of the Indian Ocean, together with systematic and biological notes on related specimens from other oceans. Discovery Reports, 27, 1 - 162." type="journal article" year="1954">Totton (1954)</bibRefCitation>
have been followed here in considering it synonymous with 
<taxonomicName authority="(Linnaeus, 1758)" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1100,1432,1789,1815]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Porpitidae" genus="Porpita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="porpita">
<emphasis box="[1100,1217,1789,1814]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">P. porpita</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Linnaeus, C." box="[1235,1423,1789,1815]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" refId="ref59798" refString="Linnaeus, C. (1758) Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. Editio decima, reformata. Laurentii Salvii, Holmiae, 823 pp." type="book" year="1758">Linnaeus, 1758</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. An account of the cnidome has been given in a previous report (
<bibRefCitation author="Calder, D. R." box="[911,1062,1829,1855]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="1 - 107" refId="ref52713" refString="Calder, D. R. (1988) Shallow-water hydroids of Bermuda: the Athecatae. Royal Ontario Museum, Life Sciences Contributions, 148, 1 - 107." type="journal article" year="1988">Calder 1988</bibRefCitation>
). Additional information on the species is given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Schuchert, P." box="[378,585,1869,1895]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" refId="ref64709" refString="Schuchert, P. (2010) The European athecate hydroids and their medusae (Hydrozoa, Cnidaria): Capitata Part 2. Revue Suisse de Zoologie, in press." type="book" year="2010">Schuchert (2010)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,1437,1229,1975]" lastBlockId="70.[151,1436,152,338]" lastPageId="70" lastPageNumber="71" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
The hydroid stage of 
<taxonomicName authority="porpita" authorityName="porpita (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[447,629,1909,1934]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Porpitidae" genus="Porpita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="porpita">
<emphasis box="[447,629,1909,1934]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Porpita porpita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a component of the open ocean pleuston, and specimens occasionally wash ashore in 
<collectingRegion box="[381,466,1949,1975]" country="United States of America" name="Hawaii" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Hawaii</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Eldredge, L. G. &amp; Devaney, D. M." box="[480,797,1949,1975]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="105 - 107" refId="ref55263" refString="Eldredge, L. G. &amp; Devaney, D. M. (1977) Other hydrozoans. In: Devaney, D. M. &amp; Eldredge, L. G. (Eds.), Reef and shore fauna of Hawaii. Section 1: Protozoa through Ctenophora. Bernice P. Bishop Museum, Special Publication, 64 (1), 105 - 107." type="journal article" year="1977">Eldredge &amp; Devaney 1977</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hoover, J. P." box="[809,965,1949,1975]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" refId="ref58355" refString="Hoover, J. P. (1998) Hawai'i's sea creatures. A guide to Hawai'i's marine invertebrates. Mutual Publishing, Honolulu, 366 pp." type="book" year="1998">Hoover 1998</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hoover, J. P." box="[976,1039,1949,1975]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" refId="ref58383" refString="Hoover, J. P. (2006) Hawai'i's sea creatures. A guide to Hawai'i's marine invertebrates. Revised edition. Mutual Publishing, Honolulu, 366 pp." type="book" year="2006">2006</bibRefCitation>
). Colonies are deep blue in colour when alive. Besides hydroid and medusa, the life cycle includes several juvenile stages, including a rataria “larva” and a young pleustonic hydroid stage.
</paragraph>
